          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
    BRICS appeals to Southeast Asia
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
       Summary: BRICS is gaining traction in Southeast Asia as a strategic alternative to the West.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          BRICS, currently expanded to include Egypt, Ethiopia, Iran, the UAE, and Indonesia, is increasingly seen as a viable alternative to Western-led institutions. Until Indonesia joined in January, Southeast Asia had been largely absent from the group. But interest is growing: Malaysia, Thailand, and Vietnam have recently decided to participate as partner nations, signaling a regional shift toward <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-3-jul-25-analysis-h1-9-engagement-with-brics?source=website" target="_blank">engagement with BRICS</a>.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        All four Southeast Asian participants have expressed interest in accessing the BRICS-led New Development Bank, which could help countries diversify their sources of foreign funding in infrastructure and green technologies. They are also interested in Contingent Reserve Arrangement, a collective monetary safety net that allows members to obtain pooled funds in times of economic distress.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         These nations view their involvement in BRICS as a strategic decision. It allows them to engage in cooperative multipolarity and express their aversion to intensifying great-power competition. Malaysia, as ASEAN chair in 2025, is already promoting BRICS-ASEAN ties and sees the bloc as a vehicle for advancing <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-3-jul-25-analysis-h1-10-south-south-cooperation?source=website" target="_blank">South-South cooperation</a>.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        However, this engagement might create friction within the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-3-jul-25-analysis-h1-11-association-of-southeast-asian-nations?source=website" target="_blank">Association of Southeast Asian Nations</a> (ASEAN), which values neutrality and consensus. Different views on China’s maritime assertions in the South China Sea already strain regional unity, and alignment with BRICS could heighten those tensions. Additionally, growing ties with the bloc risk provoking US backlash, as Trump has <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-3-jul-25-analysis-h1-12-threatened-brics?source=website" target="_blank">threatened BRICS</a> with 100% tariffs in response to their currency initiatives. 
          </p>
         
        </mj-text>
