   Why is the South China Sea a geopolitical hotspot? 
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/china-land-reclamation-south-china-sea-satellite.jpg" alt="In recent years, satellite imagery has shown China’s increased efforts to reclaim land in the South China Sea" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>In recent years, satellite imagery has shown China’s increased efforts to reclaim land in the South China Sea. Credits: CNN</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px 4px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        China, the Philippines, Vietnam, Indonesia, Malaysia, Brunei, and Taiwan all <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-3-jul-25-foundations-h1-18-contest-parts-of-the-south-china-sea?source=website" target="_blank">contest parts of the South China Sea</a>. It has become a major geopolitical hotspot due to overlapping territorial assertions, abundant natural resources, strategic maritime significance, and intensifying great-power rivalry.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-table font-family="Roboto+Serif" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" padding="10px 18px" style=" width:100%;">
            <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">→</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.6;">
             <strong>Location:</strong> Strategically positioned between Southeast Asia and the Pacific, the South China Sea serves as a key maritime artery. Over a third of global shipping, worth more than $3T annually, passes through these waters.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">→</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;line-height:1.6;">
             <strong>Natural resources:</strong> The seabed is believed to contain around around 11Bn barrels of oil and 190Tn cubic feet of natural gas, making it one of the most resource-rich maritime areas in the world.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">→</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;line-height:1.6;">
            <strong>Fishing:</strong> It is home to some of the world's most productive fisheries, accounting for roughly 12% of the global fish catch, and supporting many livelihoods in the region.</td>
            </tr>
        </mj-table>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        China's expansive assertion, known as the "<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-3-jul-25-foundations-h1-19-nine-dash-line?source=website" target="_blank">nine-dash line</a>," covers a large portion of the sea and overlaps with the economic zones of several other countries. To strengthen its demands, China has built and militarized artificial islands in the sea, actions ruled unlawful by the international courts, but still enforced on the ground.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      Tensions have risen in recent years with incidents like Chinese ships using water cannons against Philippine vessels. Many of the confrontations are fueled by national pride, concerns over sovereignty, and outside involvement, particularly from the US, which has a vested interest in this region.</p>

        </mj-text>
